The proposition is the immediate consequence of the following two claims. 

		\begin{claim}
			With respect to the theory of any structure $\mathcal{M}$ with at least two elements, the formula $x \neq y$ is equivalent to $$\psi_{\neq}(x,y):= (\forall z) \ (x=y \rightarrow z=y),$$ and is therefore equivalent to an $h$-formula.
		\end{claim}
            \begin{proof}
                By assumption $(x=y \rightarrow z=y)$ is equivalent to an $h$-formula $\phi(x,y,z)$. Therefore, from the definition of $h$-formulas, $(\forall z) \phi(x,y,z)$ is an $h$-formula equivalent to $\psi_{\neq}(x,y)$. Since $\mathcal{M}$ has at least two elements, the latter is clearly equivalent to $x\neq y$.
            \end{proof}



				\begin{claim}
					 With respect to the theory of any structure $\mathcal{M}$ with at least three elements, the formula $x=z \rightarrow y=w$ is equivalent to the following formula:
					\begin{align*}
						(\exists u)(\exists x')(\exists y') & ~\quad \psi_{\neq}(u,x)\wedge \psi_{\neq}(u,y)
						\\
						&\wedge   (x=z \leftrightarrow x'=z) \wedge  (\forall x'') \left ( (x=z \leftrightarrow x''=z) \rightarrow (x''=u \rightarrow x'=u) \right)\\
						\tag{*} \label{eq.Zsupp}&\wedge   (y=w \leftrightarrow y'=w) \wedge (\forall y'') \left ( (y=w \leftrightarrow y''=w) \rightarrow (y''=u \rightarrow y'=u)\right)\\
						& \wedge  y'=u \rightarrow x'=u.
					\end{align*}

				\end{claim}
                \begin{proof}
                    To facilitate the argument, we view the variables $x,y,z,w,\dots $ as functions from a set $A$ to the structure $\mathcal{M}$. The claim then follows if we take $A$ to be a singleton and identify  $\mathcal{M}$ with the set of functions from $A$ to  $\mathcal{M}$.
